04712nam a22007695i 9780231543521DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016029408  a(OCoLC)984688399  a97802315435217 a10.7312/komj181262doi  a(DE-B1597)480343  a(OCoLC)974567536  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPL2687.G36bZ73 2017 4aPL2687.G36 7aPHI0230002bisacsh04a895.11/422231 aKomjathy, Louis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTaming the Wild Horse :bAn Annotated Translation and Study of the Daoist Horse Taming Pictures /cLouis Komjathy. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b23 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustrations and Tables -- tAbbreviations -- tPart I. Introduction -- t1. In Search of the Wild Horse -- t2. Of Stallions, Steppes, and Stables -- tPart II. Translations -- tHorse Taming Poems -- tCommentary on the Horse Taming Poems -- tPart III. Exegesis -- tBeing with Horses -- tAppendix 1. Hagiography of Gao Daokuan (1195–1277) -- tAppendix 2. Song of Pure Awakening -- tAppendix 3. Horse-Related Technical Terminology in the Horse Taming Pictures -- tNotes -- tCharacter Glossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn thirteenth-century China, a Daoist monk named Gao Daokuan (1195-1277) composed a series of illustrated poems and accompanying verse commentary known as the Daoist Horse Taming Pictures. In this annotated translation and study, Louis Komjathy argues that this virtually unknown text offers unique insights into the transformative effects of Daoist contemplative practice. Taming the Wild Horse examines Gao's illustrated poems in terms of monasticism and contemplative practice, as well as the multivalent meaning of the "horse" in traditional Chinese culture and the consequences for both human and nonhuman animals.The Horse Taming Pictures consist of twelve poems, ten of which are equine-centered. They develop the metaphor of a "wild" or "untamed" horse to represent ordinary consciousness, which must be reined in and harnessed through sustained self-cultivation, especially meditation. The compositions describe stages on the Daoist contemplative path. Komjathy provides opportunities for reflection on contemplative practice in general and Daoist meditation in particular, which may lead to a transpersonal way of perceiving and being.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHorses in literature. 0aTaoism in literature. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Taoist.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311054330808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2017z9783110548228oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/komj1812640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231543521423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231543521/original  a978-3-11-054330-8  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2017  aZDB-23-DPHb2017